Solution:
The cross product of $\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 2 \\ -6 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ is given by the determinant \[\begin{vmatrix} \mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k} \\ 5 & 2 & -6 \\ 1 & 1 & 3 \end{vmatrix}.\]Expanding this determinant, we get \begin{align*}
\begin{vmatrix} \mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k} \\ 5 & 2 & -6 \\ 1 & 1 & 3 \end{vmatrix} &= \mathbf{i} \begin{vmatrix} 2 & -6 \\ 1 & 3 \end{vmatrix} - \mathbf{j} \begin{vmatrix} 5 & -6 \\ 1 & 3 \end{vmatrix} + \mathbf{k} \begin{vmatrix} 5 & 2 \\ 1 & 1 \end{vmatrix} \\
&= \mathbf{i} (2 \cdot 3 - (-6) \cdot 1) - \mathbf{j} (5 \cdot 3 - (-6) \cdot 1) + \mathbf{k} (5 \cdot 1 - 2 \cdot 1) \\
&= \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 20 \\ -21 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}}.
\end{align*}

