Since $CH$ is an altitude of triangle $CAF,$
\[\tan A = \frac{HF}{AF} = \frac{6}{AF}.\]Since $AF$ is an altitude of triangle $ABC,$
\[\tan A = \frac{2K}{AB \cdot CF} = \frac{K}{AB \cdot CF/2},\]where $K$ is the area of triangle $ABC.$

Since $CH$ is an altitude of triangle $ABC,$
\[\frac{AB \cdot CH}{2} = K.\]Also, $AB = CF/\sin C,$ so
\[\tan A = \frac{2K}{AB \cdot CF} = \frac{4K \sin C}{CF^2} = \frac{2 \cdot CH \sin C}{CF^2}.\]Since $CH = HC = 15,$ $\tan A = \frac{2 \cdot 15 \sin C}{CF^2} = \frac{30 \sin C}{CF^2}.$

Since $HC = 15$ and $HF = 6,$ $FC = HC - HF = 9.$  Then $\triangle CEF$ is a right triangle, so by the Pythagorean theorem,
\[EF^2 = EC^2 - CF^2 = \left( \frac{BC \cdot \sin C}{\sin B} \right)^2 - CF^2.\]Since $BC = 2K/AC = 2K/(CF/\sin C) = 2K \sin C/CF,$
\[EF^2 = \left( \frac{2K \sin C}{CF \sin B} \right)^2 - CF^2.\]Also, $AF = K/BC = K/(2K \sin C/CF) = CF/(2 \sin C),$ so
\[\tan B = \frac{EF}{AF} = \frac{\sqrt{EF^2}}{AF} = \frac{\sqrt{\left( \frac{2K \sin C}{CF \sin B} \right)^2 - CF^2}}{CF/(2 \sin C)}.\]Hence,
\begin{align*}
\tan A \tan B &= \frac{30 \sin C}{CF^2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{\left( \frac{2K \sin C}{CF \sin B} \right)^2 - CF^2}}{CF/(2 \sin C)} \\
&= \frac{60 K \sin^2 C}{CF^3 \sin B} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{1}{\sin^2 B} - \frac{CF^2}{4K^2 \sin^2 C}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^3 \sin B} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{AB^2 - CF^2}{\sin^2 B}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2 \sin B} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{AB + CF}{AB - CF}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2 \sin B} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{AB/CF + 1}{AB/CF - 1}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2 \sin B} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{\sin^2 C/\sin^2 B + 1}{\sin^2 C/\sin^2 B - 1}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{\sin^2 C + \sin^2 B}{\sin^2 C - \sin^2 B}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{2 - 2 \cos A}{2 \cos A}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2} \cdot \sqrt{\frac{1 - \cos A}{\cos A}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2} \sin (A/2)}{\sqrt{1 + \cos A}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2} \sqrt{\frac{1 - \cos A}{2}}}{\sqrt{2 \cos^2 (A/2)}} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{1 - \cos A}}{\cos (A/2)} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin^2 C}{CF^2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2 \sin^2 (A/2)}}{\cos (A/2)} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin (A/2) \sin C}{CF \cos (A/2)} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin (A/2) \sin B \sin C}{CF \sin B \cos (A/2)} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin (A/2) \sin B \sin C}{AF \cos (A/2)} \\
&= \frac{60 \sin (A/2) \sin B \sin C}{HF}.
\end{align*}Finally, $HF = 6,$ so
\[\tan A \tan B = \frac{60 \sin (A/2) \sin B \sin C}{6} = \boxed{10 \sin (A/2) \sin B \sin C}.\]

